<br>
Dusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 518<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/7/02 2:17:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator</span><hr size=1> Technically the counterweight isn't in geosync but just a bit above it.  I thought Bob Munck over at the space elevator forum explained it well.  Here's what he said:<br>
<br>
&quot;The counterweight has inertia, and therefore wants to continue moving in a straight line, but its path is pulled into a circle by the cable and the rotating Earth.  This makes there appear to be an outward &quot;centrifugal&quot; force through the center of rotation of the Earth and the counterweight.  An ascending climber adds a tiny westward force against the cable while it is moving upwards, causing the SE to lean very, very slightly to the west.  In essence, the climber pulls back on the Earth through the cable to acquire its additional angular momentum.<br>
<br>
When the climber stops, the cable returns to its upright (and locked) position.  Note that the force generated by the climber is tiny, just a few newtons, as it masses on the order of 1% the mass of the cable and takes several days to go from .46 km/sec to 2.8 km/sec.  The Earth's rotation slows down a bit, but we'd have to send Australia up a Space Elevator to get a noticable effect.<br>
<br>
There are probably a lot of problems that haven't been considered yet, but not something as elementary as conservation of angular momentum.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orstio>Orstio</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of Everything Space</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/7/02 5:48:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.everything-space.com/images/crab2_med[1].jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator</span><hr size=1> I think the real problem with the space elevator lies in the fact that the magnetic potential at the Earth's surface is different than that in GEO.<br>
<br>
Anyone remember the tethered-satellite experiments?  Here's a link:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/er/seh/Tethered_Satellites.pdf">www.jsc.nasa.gov/er/seh/T...llites.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>On STS-75, the satellite was extended 19.7 kilometers when the tether broke near the boom. The satellite and tether drifted away safely from the orbiter and were not retrievable. Up to the time of the severing of the tether, the orbiter-tethered satellite system had been generating 3,500 volts and up to 0.5 amps of current. Later investigation of the problems that occurred on the two missions determined that the tether on the first flight was snagged by the mechanism that unreeled it from the orbiter. The break of the tether on the second mission occurred because of either a flaw in the<br>
insulation or the penetration of a foreign object into the insulation causing an electrical arc from the tether to a nearby ground. The arcing severed the tether.<br>
<br>
In spite of these problems, each major objective was met. The flights demonstrated that the tethered satellite would deploy and the forces acting on the satellite and the orbiter worked to keep the satellite extended from the orbiter without additional thruster firing. Both missions also demonstrated that tethered satellites will generate an electric current as they pass through Earth's magnetic field.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And a pic of the tether:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://liftoff.msfc.nasa.gov/Shuttle/STS-75/tss-1r/hw/tether_layers.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
If enough electricity was generated over the distance of 19.7 km that an arc across several meters burnt the tether right off, imagine the amount of electricty generated by a cable extending from the Earth's surface to GEO.  How would anyone insulate this so no arcing would occur?  <p><a href="http://pub80.ezboard.com/beverythingspace">Everything Space</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 521<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/7/02 6:24:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator Upstarts Settle Down To Business</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If enough electricity was generated over the distance of 19.7 km that an arc across several meters burnt the tether right off, imagine the amount of electricty generated by a cable extending from the Earth's surface to GEO. How would anyone insulate this so no arcing would occur? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You have to remember that unlike the tether experiment conducted by NASA, the space elevator's ribbon wouldn't be dragging through the atmosphere but rather will be stationary in relation to it.  Even though the ribbon will build up a bit of a charge it's not likely to be overwhelming and it certainly won't generate electricity the way the NASA experiment did.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 12/7/02 6:25:18 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orstio>Orstio</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lord of Everything Space</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/7/02 8:06:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.everything-space.com/images/crab2_med[1].jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator Upstarts Settle Down To Business</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You have to remember that unlike the tether experiment conducted by NASA, the space elevator's ribbon wouldn't be dragging through the atmosphere but rather will be stationary in relation to it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The magnetic field of the Earth is created in the mantle, not in the atmosphere, so speed relative to the atmosphere is irrelevant.  It would be speed relative to the magnetic field, which changes constantly, independent of the Earth's rotational velocity.<br>
<br>
The real math here is the Lorenz Force:  B x V x L = voltage<br>
<br>
B is the measurement of Earth's magnetic field strength, which averages 3*10^-5 tesla.<br>
<br>
V is the velocity of the cable in relation to the Earth's magnetic field.  Let's say, for argument's sake, that the cable wobbles at a speed of only 0.1 m/s (This is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">VERY</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> stable, considering the speed that the tops of tall buildings wobble in the wind, and the variation of the magnetic field.)<br>
<br>
L is the length of the cable.  Geosynchronous orbit is 35,788 km, or 35,788,000 meters from the surface of the Earth.<br>
<br>
So, the equation for the voltage drop is: (3*10^-5)(0.1)(35,788,000)<br>
<br>
which equals:  1073.64 Volts<br>
<br>
If we insert this number into Ohm's law, and assume that the conductivity of the cable is equal or better than that of copper, we get an amperage of at least:<br>
<br>
V=IR<br>
1073.64=I(500)<br>
I=2.14728 amps<br>
<br>
1000 volts at 2 amps will arc quite a distance, if there is a nearby conductor (like the elevator, travelling up and down the cable).<br>
<br>
Joule also showed that the work done in a circuit is converted into heat at the rate of:<br>
<br>
P=(I^2)*R<br>
<br>
So, the heat generation (in Watts) is:<br>
<br>
P=(2.14728^2)(500)<br>
P=2305.4056 Watts<br>
<br>
2300 Watts adds up to a lot of heat, when the wire is running 24/7 (There really is no way to shut it off.)  One would have to ensure the cable ends were secured without a change in conductivity, because the energy is released most at &quot;weak&quot; points, like splices, connections, and minute variations in the cable. <br>
<br>
Please note that:<br>
<br>
a)  If a substance is used that is more conductive than copper, the amperage will increase, thus creating a greater chance of arcing/greater potential arc distance.<br>
<br>
b) If a substance is used that is less conductive, more heat is generated, with a greater chance of burning connections or insulation at &quot;weak&quot; points in the cable.<br>
<br>
<br>
I'm not saying that this makes the space elevator impossible, I'm saying that it will be one of their greatest challenges, especially in proving the safety of the system.  I'd hate to be half-way up the elevator and have one of the cables arc and burn off.   It would also need a maintenance system that would allow for a reliable method of replacement of cables due to wear and tear from the movement of the elevator. <p><a href="http://pub80.ezboard.com/beverythingspace">Everything Space</a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orstio>Orstio</A> at: 12/7/02 8:21:55 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 522<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/8/02 12:13:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator Upstarts Settle Down To Business</span><hr size=1> Good info, I'll go asking some questions.  I've looked up the problem of electromagnetic fields in Brad Edwards final NIAC report and he doesn't seem to think the heating will be any serious hurdle but he mentions nothing (at least so far as I've read) of the electrical dangers that might await the climbers (perhaps he's assuming most of the energy will be converted into heat and radiated away?).  Here's a section I quoted out of the work:<br>
<br>
&quot;Heating of the cable can be produced by passage through the local magnetic fields. The potential induced along the cable can be expressed as: E = B(r)v(r) where E is in volts/meter, B(r) is the magnetic field, and v(r) is the velocity of the cable relative to the magnetic field. For radii (r) &lt;10rEarth, B(r) ~ 0.35_10-4rEarth 3/r3 and v(r) is approximately zero. However, if we assume the worst possible case where the magnetic field is fixed and the cable is rotating with the Earth (v(r) = 463 r/rEarth m/s) we get potentials from 0.00026 V/m at 10rEarth to 0.016 V/m at Earth’s surface. At distances of greater than 10rE, the cable is in the interplanetary magnetic field during the day (Bave ~6 nT and Bmax ~80 nT) and is in the Earth’s magnetosphere at night. This corresponds to a maximum potential of 0.00068 V/m at the far end of the cable. With a minimum resistance of 0.4 W/m we have a maximum of 0.0064 W/m of heating occurring near the Earth end of the cable and 1 mW at the far end. The cable would quickly radiate this level of heating away into space.&quot; <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 12/8/02 12:17:11 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2667<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/8/02 1:09:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=518.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Space Elevator Upstarts Settle Down To Business</span><hr size=1> It sounds like the perfect solution to delivering pa